# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1909-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The 1882 season was the first for the **Alleghenys**, later known as the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] They finished at exactly a .500 record, 39 wins and 39 losses, good for fourth place in the new American Association.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The team played its home games in Allegheny City, across the Allegheny River from Pittsburgh.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] Chartered as the Allegheny Base Ball Club of Pittsburgh, the team appeared as "Allegheny" in the standings and was often referred to in the plural as the Alleghenys.
[src:1909-world-series/1882-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The club was not related to the earlier Alleghenys of the International Association.
[src:1909-world-series/1883-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1883 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the second season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1909-world-series/1883-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished seventh in the American Association with a record of 31–67.
[src:1909-world-series/1884-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1884 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the third season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1909-world-series/1884-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished 11th in the American Association with a record of 30–78.
[src:1909-world-series/1885-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1885 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the fourth season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1909-world-series/1885-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished third in the American Association with a record of 56–55.
[src:1909-world-series/1886-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1886 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the fifth season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise.
[src:1909-world-series/1886-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished second in the American Association with a record of 80–57.
[src:1909-world-series/1887-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The **1887 Pittsburgh Alleghenys season** was the sixth season of the Pittsburgh Alleghenys franchise and its first in the National League, where they remain to this day.
[src:1909-world-series/1887-pittsburgh-alleghenys-season] The Alleghenys finished sixth in the standings with a record of 55–69.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The **1909 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1909 season.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The sixth edition of the World Series, it featured the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion Detroit Tigers.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Pirates won the Series in seven games to capture their first championship of the modern Major League Baseball era and the second championship in the club's history.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Pittsburgh-based team.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] This Series is best remembered for featuring two of the very best players of the time, Pittsburgh shortstop Honus Wagner, and Detroit outfielder Ty Cobb.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Sites: games 1, 2 in Pittsburgh; games 3, 4 in Detroit; game 5 in Pittsburgh; games 6, 7 in Detroit.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Pirates had won the National League pennant in 1909 behind the brilliant play of Honus Wagner, who led the league with a .339 batting average and 100 runs batted in.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Detroit returned for their third consecutive Fall Classic, determined to erase the memories of their previous efforts.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Tigers were also backed up by the heavy bat of Ty Cobb (who had just won his third consecutive American League batting title) and a formidable pitching staff.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] They might have finally won the Series in their third try, had it not been for Pirates rookie Babe Adams.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Manager Fred Clarke started him, on a hunch, in Game 1.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Adams won that game and two more, setting a World Series record for rookies.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Tigers thus became the first AL team to win three consecutive pennants and the first team to lose three straight World Series (the New York Giants would lose three straight Series from 1911 to 1913).
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Pirates ran at will against the weak Detroit catching corps, stealing 18 bases in seven games.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] For the first time, four umpires were used at the same time, with the standard plate umpire and base umpire along with two outfield umpires.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] On June 14, 2009, the series' 100th anniversary was celebrated, when the Tigers and Pirates played each other in Pittsburgh.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Both teams wore throwback uniforms similar to those worn in 1909.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The stadium's public address and sound systems were also turned off, simulating the game conditions in 1909.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Ty Cobb had a fairly quiet Series, going 6-for-26 with two stolen bases and one caught stealing.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] There is a long-standing legend that Cobb, standing on first base, called the German-ancestored Honus Wagner a "krauthead", told him he was going to steal second, and was not only thrown out but that Wagner tagged him in the mouth, ball in hand, drawing blood from Cobb's lip.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] However, an examination of the play-by-play does not indicate that such a play occurred.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] In the one "caught stealing" charged to Cobb, during the first inning of Game 4, he was actually safe at second due to a throwing error by first baseman Bill Abstein.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] This story is largely attributed to the creative press at the time, and Wagner and Cobb were actually on good terms.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Rookie Babe Adams, who had compiled a 12–3 record during the regular season, unexpectedly drew the start for Game 1.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] He responded with a six-hit, 4–1 victory sparked by Clarke's game-tying home run in the bottom of the fourth inning.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Tigers began their 7–2 comeback win (after a two-run Pirate bottom of the first) with three runs in the top of the third, tying the Series at one game apiece.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Honus Wagner had three hits, three RBI and three stolen bases as the Pirates regained the lead in the Series, two games to one.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The win-swapping continued with Detroit taking Game 4.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Tiger ace George Mullin threw a five-hit shutout while striking out 10 Pirates, again evening the Series at two games apiece.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Babe Adams threw another six-hitter, for an 8–4 triumph and a 3–2 Series lead for his Pirates.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Mullin, after being roughed up for three first-inning runs, surrendered only one more and wound up with the win, knotting the Series at three games apiece.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] With the Series coming down to a climactic seventh game (the first to go the distance), Pittsburgh's Fred Clarke went with two-game winner Babe Adams as his pitcher, while Detroit Manager Hugh Jennings decided on Bill Donovan, a complete-game winner in Game 2.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] He hit the first Pirate batter and went on to walk six in the first two innings.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] He was pulled after three with Adams confidently holding a 2–0 lead.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Pittsburgh never looked back, as Babe nailed his third six-hitter and third win of the Series for an 8–0 championship victory.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Honus Wagner continued to prove his Cooperstown worthiness by hitting .333, with seven RBI and six stolen bases (the latter total standing as a Series record until Lou Brock surpassed it in 1967).
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] On the other side, Ty Cobb did not fare as well.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Appearing in what would be his last Series (although he would remain active through 1928), Cobb batted only .231 although he did lead the Tigers, losers of their third Series in three years, with six RBI.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] It was the first time that one team won the odd-numbered games; the other, the even; it did not happen again until 1962.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The championship was recorded by Essanay Co., and sold double the expected number of copies.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] Kennedy speculated that the film would set a world record for sales.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] No two professional sports teams from Detroit and Pittsburgh would play for a major professional sports championship again until the 2008 Stanley Cup Final between the Detroit Red Wings and Pittsburgh Penguins.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Pirates would return to the World Series in 1925, where they overcame a 3–1 series deficit and defeated the Washington Senators in seven games.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] This was the third straight Would Series loss for the Tigers.
[src:1909-world-series/1909-world-series] The Tigers would not play in another Fall Classic for 25 years, where they lost yet again in seven games, this time to the St.
